1854, 1909, 1923-2014 The Time Inc. Annex Files is an assembled collection created by the archivists at Time Inc. of materials considered too bulky or infrequently requested to be housed in the main archives. Records in the Annex Files seem to be an extension of the of the materials in the Time Inc. Subject Files (MS 3009-RG 1) and document the history of Time Inc. as an organization with information on each publication and many departments at Time Inc. The collection is largely made up of records pertaining to the development of magazines, The March of Time, Home Box Office (HBO), Time-Life Books, and information on public affairs programs and events, international business, and advertising studies and surveys. These materials are stored offsite and advance notice is required for use. Please contact manuscripts@nyhistory.org prior to your research visit to coordinate access. Keep in mind that it will take up to five (5) business days for collections to arrive, and you should plan your research accordingly.
Conditions Governing Access
Open to qualified researchers with the exception of restricted materials. Restricted materials may include contracts and consent forms. Restricted materials are located in boxes R40, R41, and R69-R85. Unreformatted audiovisual and digital material in the collection is not accessible. Materials are stored offsite and advance notice is required for use.
Arrangement
The collection is arranged alphabetically based on the original arrangement.
Historical Note
The Time Inc. Annex Files were assembled by the archivists at Time Inc. from materials considered too bulky or infrequently requested to be housed in the main archives. The archivists moved these records from the Time Inc. Archives' Library to a lower floor within the Time Inc. building to save space. The materials were housed in the building's sub-basement prior to the 2015 donation donated to the New-York Historical Society in 2015.
Citation: Hooper, Bill. Email to Holly Deakyne, 2016 June 10.
Provenance
Gift of Time Inc. in 2015.
Preferred Citation
This collection should be cited as Time Inc. Annex Files, MS 3009-RG 39, New-York Historical Society.
Processing Information
The Time Inc. Annex Files were partially processed by Samantha Brown in 2019 and 2020 and completed by Allen Thomas in 2020. The original folders were retained although some documents were transferred to archival containers in instances of overcrowding or if no original folder was present. Thomas and Brown created the inventory and other descriptive notes for the record group. Materials were arranged in their original order unless no order was present then an order was imposed.
Related Materials
This finding aid relates to just one record group of the Time Inc. Records. For information about the other record groups and for overall information about the archives, please see the Guide to the Time Inc. Records (MS 3009). The Henry Luce Papers (MS 3014) were acquired with the Time Inc. Records. The collection of books acquired with the records are cataloged as the Time Inc. Reference Library.
Due to the nature of this collection described in the Historial Note many of the other record groups in the Time Inc. Records contain related materials.
Scope and Contents
The Time Inc. Annex Files seem to be an extension of the materials in the Time Inc. Subject Files (MS 3009-RG 1) documenting the history of Time Inc. as an organization and have information on each publication and many departments at Time Inc. The Subject Files were assembled for use by writers and researchers working on three authorized volumes of Time Inc. history, and the Annex Files were presumably not part of this project.
The Annex Files are made up of a variety of content including annual reports, advertisements, agreements, briefs, clippings, committee reports, contracts, correspondence, directories, drafts, financial information and studies, guidelines, magazines, memoranda, polices, press releases, project proposals, promotional material, reports, staff lists, studies, surveys and other documents regarding Time Inc.'s functioning as a business.
The topics of these materials include but are not limited to: Time Inc.'s magazines such as Architectural Forum, Fortune, Life, People, Sports Illustrated, Time, and smaller titles; the various departments and divisions within Time Inc. such as Time-Life Books, Home Box Office (HBO), and Corporate Development; The March of Time newsreels and radio program; international business studies and agreements; marketing studies and surveys; records on public affairs programs and conferences; samples of non-Time Inc. publications for study, and "war task" information and propaganda material produced by Time Inc. in cooperation with the United States government during the Second World War for both civilian and military consumption.
Conditions Governing Use
This collection is owned by the New-York Historical Society. Although the N-YHS owns this collection as physical property, the donor specifically retains all copyright and all other proprietary rights which may exist. The copyright law of the United States governs the making of photocopies and protects unpublished materials as well as published materials. Unpublished materials created before January 1, 1978 cannot be quoted in publication without permission of the copyright holder.
